* * * * * <br>
<br>
Mr Kingham is sitting as his desk when he hears a knock at the door.<br>
<br>
&quot;Come in,&quot; he booms from within the inner sanctum.<br>
<br>
Hurriedly, Miss Butteridge tiptoes into the room, new recruit in tow. &quot;Hello Sir,&quot; she twitters. &quot;I have a Mr Granger here to see you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Miss Butteridge,&quot; asks Mr Kingham, with an tone of concern in his voice. &quot;I asked you to keep the visitors out for the day.&quot; Mr Kingham remains behind his computer screen.<br>
<br>
Miss Butteridge folds her arms and squints a little. &quot;Mr Kingham. This is your interviewee for the position of Senior Designer.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;...mmm?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll leave you two to get acquainted,&quot; says Miss Butteridge, rather frostily, as she leaves the room. She tries to slam the door, but the spring mechanism prevents any such thing from occurring. However, the soundproofing - or lack of it - does not prevent us from hearing Miss Butteridge's conversation in the next sector.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm sorry, he's rather busy right now,&quot; she chirps. &quot;However, I could just leave you in his office and see if he acknowledges you. We've got one in there at the moment.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mr Granger looks uncomfortably at the door.<br>
<br>
&quot;...SUPER, we'll see you at 9 o'clock tomorrow morning,&quot; tweets Miss Butteridge from beyond. Then the outside offices lull down to a silent hum, and Mr Granger realises that he is alone with the IT Director in his den.<br>
<br>
Kingham takes his eyes off the screen for a moment, and flicks through his diary. &quot;Let's see... Gr... Gr... Gra...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Granger?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No, no, can't be him. We thought his CV was terrible.&quot;<br>
<br>
Granger turns to face Kingham's desk. &quot;Is that so?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, he was a shocking fellow, according to my secretary. If we signed him up, we'd have to fire him right away. Or make him head of the Marketing department. Now THAT would be a punishment.&quot;<br>
<br>
Granger looks at the floor. Kingham demands, &quot;so, man, what have you got to say for yourself?&quot;<br>
<br>
Granger thinks for a moment. &quot;Well, Sir, have you ever considered the merits of your Marketing department?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Merits, man? MERITS?! ... no I haven't actually. Do they have them over there?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;They certainly do, Sir. Apparently, the right candidate can go right to the top in a VERY short space of time. Much quicker than in IT.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kingham looks puzzled. &quot;Is that so?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, they are a shocking department, according to the agency. If they sign people up, they have to promote them right away. And when they can't be promoted any further, they get transferred to the IT department. Now THAT would be a punishment.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kingham looks at the floor. Granger asks, &quot;so, Sir, what can I do for you today?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kingham thinks for a moment. &quot;Well, man, have you ever considered the merits of our IT department?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Actually, I was looking for a job in Marketing.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kingham thinks carefully. This could be a chance to punish this slimy little man. &quot;No, man, I'd like to sign you up for IT. I think you'd do a great job of it. How would you like to be our Senior Designer?&quot;<br>
<br>
Granger replies, &quot;If that is what you want.&quot; He turns to leave the room.<br>
<br>
Kingham calls to Granger, &quot;Name?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What?&quot; Granger opens the door.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your name, man, your name.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Granger,&quot; he replies, walking through the doorway and closing the door behind him.<br>
<br>
Kingham sits quietly for a moment, and looks at his diary. &quot;Granger? I was meant to see him at 9:00 this morning.&quot; Kingham looks at the Jedi clock on the wall. 9:15.<br>
<br>
The phone rings. Kingham picks it up. &quot;Hello?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Granger, Sir. If you wish, you can see me at 9:00 NEXT Monday morning, and we'll recap.&quot;<br>
<br>
Puzzled, Kingham says, &quot;I'll see you then. What was the name again?&quot;<br>
<br>
Granger replies, &quot;Granger, Sir. Senior Designer. See you on Monday.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kingham carefully puts the receiver back on the base unit, and sits quietly for a moment. Suddenly, he slams the palms of both hands on the table, and stands up. &quot;Why does he need to visit an agency to book a meeting with me? I've got a secretary for goodness sake!&quot;<br>
