* * * * * <br>
<br>
He gets out of his car, and immobilises it. With a ninja kick, he attempts to immobilise a nearby lamp post, and breaks his foot.<br>
<br>
&quot;Arrrrrrgh!!&quot; he wails, holding his foot in his hand, as if it will make the pain go away.<br>
<br>
&quot;Mr Kingham?&quot; twitters a familiar voice. &quot;Are you all right?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kingham stands up quickly and salutes. &quot;Yes, I'm fine,&quot; he says. After a brief pause: &quot;Argh! Blood rush!&quot; With that, Kingham collapses in a heap on the pavement.<br>
<br>
* * * * * <br>
<br>
Back in his office, Kingham stares at the seemingly random ASCII characters on the screen. He has a pounding headache and can barely focus on the screen. He doesn't hear the knock at the door, and continues trying to decipher the array of letters and numbers.<br>
<br>
The knock grows more impatient with the second try, as if the visitor sees Kingham through the windowless door. Maybe x-ray vision isn't just a theory.<br>
<br>
All of a sudden, Kingham looks away from his screen, and hears the third knock. &quot;Are you in there, Sir?&quot;<br>
<br>
A little flustered, Kingham says, &quot;come in,&quot; in a less than booming voice. Granger makes his way across the threshold, and infiltrates the desk area. &quot;Take a seat,&quot; says Kingham. Granger sits. Kingham looks back at his screen, thinking he might be able to understand what's going on.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sir, I have been working on the document you asked me to do. I was wondering if you could proof read it for me?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kingham looks away from his screen, and appears to be somewhat baffled. &quot;Which document would this be, man?&quot;<br>
<br>
Granger frowns a little. &quot;Sir, you asked for a high level design of the new corporate web site.&quot; He places a thin document on Kingham's desk. Now it is Kingham's turn to frown. Reading the title aloud, he acts as if he has never heard of the document before: &quot;Design document for the new corporate web site, by Archibald E. Granger.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I was a little unsure of the title, so I decided to keep to simple.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What does the E stand for?&quot;<br>
<br>
Granger frowns again. &quot;Sir, please can you give me your comments by next Thursday?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ethan? 'Enry? I bet it's Edward.&quot;<br>
<br>
Granger turns to leave the office. &quot;Thank you, Sir. I will speak to you next week.&quot; He leaves.<br>
<br>
Kingham turns back to his screen. Suddenly, the ASCII characters make sense. &quot;It's Jennifer Lopez!!&quot;<br>
<br>
* * * * * <br>
<br>
Puzzled, Miss Butteridge puts the phone down and starts typing. Who was on the other end? Was it a prank call? She jumps as the phone rings again.<br>
<br>
&quot;H-Hello, FQK Soft Limited?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Hi, I was wondering if I could speak to a Mr Frederick Kingham please?&quot;<br>
<br>
Miss Butteridge calms down a little. &quot;I'm afraid he's unavailable right now, can I ask who's calling please?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;This is PC Thomson of the Metropolitan Police. We would like to ask Mr Kingham some questions relating to an act of vandalism in the Green Palace Car Park at 8 o'clock this morning. Do you know when I might be able to contact him, please?&quot;<br>
<br>
Miss Butteridge looks quite worried. &quot;Do you mean when he kicked a lamp post this morning?&quot;<br>
<br>
PC Thomson sounds amused. &quot;You were there? What happened?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't know, but he really hurt his foot. He was going to sue the council.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Why did he do it?&quot;<br>
<br>
Deadly serious, Miss Butteridge says, &quot;It was giving him a really funny look.&quot;<br>
<br>
PC Thomson pauses for a moment. &quot;Did you take your medication this morning, love?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Knew I'd forgotten something. Thanks!&quot; With that, Miss Butteridge hangs up the phone, and goes to lunch.<br>
